</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/yevgeny-prigozhin-wagner-group-flag-bakhmut-ukraine.png" alt="Yevgeny Prigozhin holding a Russian national flag in front of his soldiers. The soldiers are holding the Wagner Group flag in Bakhmut, Ukraine" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Yevgeny Prigozhin holding a Russian national flag in front of his soldiers. The soldiers are holding the Wagner Group flag in Bakhmut, Ukraine. Credits: AFP</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The Wagner group didn‚Äôt go anywhere. Instead, it has evolved into another shape. The death of Russian businessman Yevgeny Prigozhin in a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-04-2025-f1-11-2023-plane-crash" target="_blank">2023 plane crash</a> sparked speculation about the group's future. Many believed the group would collapse. They were wrong.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Under their renewed disguise, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-04-2025-f1-12-africa-corps" target="_blank">Africa Corps</a>, the Wagner fighters are still engaged in the Central African Republic, Mali, and Belarus. Analysts also observed that different militant groups adopted Wagner's name and symbols. Russia is tightly integrating mercenary forces into official structures, creating a more sustainable system. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Experts refer to this as the ‚Äú<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-04-2025-f1-13-wagnerization" target="_blank">Wagnerization</a>‚Äù of the Russian military. Lessons from Wagner‚Äôs operations in Bakhmut and other areas are being used in Ukraine. Western governments worry about this, but countering these forces is tricky. This is especially true in areas where the West has pulled back.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Russian journalist Ilya Barabanov believes that the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-04-2025-f1-14-original-wagner-doesnt-exist" target="_blank">original Wagner doesn‚Äôt exist</a> anymore. He pointed out that newer factions of the private military group are more risk-averse, tightly integrated with the Russian army, and regularly coordinate their activities with Russian military intelligence.</p>
        </mj-text>
